    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-03-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="212"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d212">
                <head>212. Memorandum From the Department of State Executive Secretary (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RBH1" type="from">Read</persName>) to the President’s Special
                    Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2" type="to"
                        >Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d212fn1">Source:
                        Department of State, EB/<gloss target="#t_ICD1">ICD</gloss>/<gloss
                            target="#t_TRP1">TRP</gloss> Files: Lot 75 <gloss target="#t_D1"
                            >D</gloss> 462, Sugar, New Legislation. Limited Official Use. Drafted by
                        G. Hilliker (S/S) on March 21 and cleared by <persName corresp="#p_JJ5"
                            >Jacobson</persName> (<gloss target="#t_E1">E</gloss>).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-03-21">March 21, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Sugar Legislation</item>
                </list>
                <p>We have been discussing with Agriculture and other agencies concerned the fact
                    that sugar legislation must soon be considered in anticipation of expiration of
                    the 1961 Sugar Act<note n="2" xml:id="d212fn2">Reference is to P.L. 87–15 of
                        March 31, 1961, “To Amend and Extend the Sugar Act of 1948, as Amended.” (75
                        Stat. 40)</note> on December 31. We are in general agreement on
                    recommendations to be made to the President but differ on one major point:
                    whether a substantial portion of supplies now coming from abroad should,
                    instead, be supplied domestically. The agencies are preparing a statement of the
                    problem and proposed solutions for consideration by the President. This is
                    simply to alert you to that arrangement and to the fact that a decision will
                    have to be made as soon as possible after our statement is received, inasmuch as
                    Chairman Cooley contemplates hearings in the near future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">J.W. Davis</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d212fn3">
                            <persName>Davis</persName> signed for <persName corresp="#p_RBH1"
                                >Read</persName> above <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Read</persName>’s
                            typed signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
